Looks like some problematically compressed (i.e., approx equal values) for a couple subjects: 849971 and 161832. This is seen as the kink in their QQ plots.

I’ll threshold these subjects’ data at \(rt > 500\) to eliminate this issue. A total of 25 removed from 849971 and 16 for 161832.

stroop.pro.rt <- stroop.pro.rt[!(stroop.pro.rt$subj %in% c("849971", "161832") & stroop.pro.rt$rt < 500), ]
stroop.pro.rt %>%
  filter(subj %in% c("849971", "161832")) %>%
  full_join(group_by(., subj) %>% summarize(r2norm = qqr2(rt)), by = "subj") %>%
  ggplot(aes(sample = rt)) +
  stat_qq(alpha = 0.8, size = 0.4) +
  stat_qq_line(size = 0.25) +
  facet_wrap(vars(subj)) +
  geom_text(
    aes(
      x = -1.25, y = 2000,
      label = paste0("r^2 = ", round(r2norm, 3))
      ), size = 3, color = "grey50"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 10) +

    title    = "after exclusion of rt < 500",

  • fit0 vs fit1.hom: assuming homogeneous variance across individuals, Stroop effect is variable across individuals
  • fit1.hom vs fit1.het: homogeneity of variance assumption is violated: substantial variance exists in RT across subjects in overall RT
  • fit1.het vs fit1.het1: further, variance not only differs across subjects, but within subject, across trial types (incon, congr).
    • although here, the statistics do not agree. BIC indicates the more parsimonious fit1.het is better, whereas LRT and AIC indicate the additional subj*trial.type variances are warranted.
  • fit1.het1 vs fit0.het1: when this subject*trial.type variance is modeled, the variance in the stroop effect across subjects remains.

It is clear that

  1. subjects differ in the size of the stroop effect
  2. subjects also differ in the level of ‘noise’ (level-1 variance)

movign forward, I will try to use additional information to assess which model to prefer between fit1.het and fit.het1.

diagnostics

assessing split-half-consistency

Here I assess the split-half consistency, or cross-run correlation, via the heterogeneous model. First I fit a model containing an interaction between trial.type and run, for each subject:

Within this model, there are two estimates available of the consistency or correlation between split halves.

  1. One is conditional on the observed data (y). This is obtained by extracting the “conditional modes” of the estimate, and estimating pearson’s correlation between them. These conditional modes are the most likely value of \(b\), given (conditioned on) y; i.e., the random slopes for each subject.

  2. the other method gives a correlation statistic that is not conditioned on the data, but rather is marginalized across all possible values of the data (“unconditional”). What this means exactly I don’t know. But see here or here for further reading.

Note that because of the way I coded the trial.type and run variables in my model, I will need to do some algebra to get the stroop effects and (co)variance thereof in each run.

m <- rbind(c(0, 1, 0, 0), c(0, 1, 0, 1))  ## a contrast matrix that gives us what we want

outlier exclusion

stroop.pro.rt$resid.p <- resid(fit1.het.reml, type = "p")

farout <- function(x) {
  
  q1 <- quantile(x, 0.25)
  q3 <- quantile(x, 0.75)
  iqr3 <- IQR(x) * 3
  
  x < (q1 - iqr3) | x > (q3 + iqr3)
  
}

stroop.pro.rt$is.far.out <- farout(stroop.pro.rt$resid.p)

plot(
  stroop.pro.rt$resid.p,

fit1.het.run.reml.trim <- lme(
  rt ~ trial.type * run, stroop.pro.rt, ~ trial.type * run | subj,
  weights = varIdent(form = ∼ 1 | subj),
  control = cl1,
  method = "REML",
  subset = !is.far.out
  )

## conditional covariances

u.trim <- as.matrix(coef(fit1.het.run.reml.trim)) %*% t(m)
cov(u.trim)
##       [,1]  [,2]
## [1,] 806.8 846.5
## [2,] 846.5 983.5
(r.conditional.trim <- cor(u.trim)[1, 2])  ## correlation of conditional modes
## [1] 0.9504
## unconditional / marginal covariances

tau.trim <- getVarCov(fit1.het.run.reml.trim)
(tau.trim <- m %*% tau.trim %*% t(m))
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,] 1124 1151
## [2,] 1151 1305
(r.marginal.trim <- cov2cor(tau.trim)[1, 2])
## [1] 0.9503
u.trim <- as.data.frame(u.trim)

names(u.trim) <- c("stroop.run1", "stroop.run2")

u.trim %>%
  ggplot(aes(stroop.run1, stroop.run2)) +
  geom_abline() +
  stat_boot_ci(n = 1E4, alpha = 0.2) +
  # geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "grey30") +
  geom_point(shape = 21, color = "white", fill = "black", size = 2) +
  annotate(
    geom = "text", label = paste0("r(unconditional) = ", round(r.marginal.trim, 2)), 
    y = 150, x = 20, vjust = 1, hjust = 0
    ) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank())
